  "prompt": "Is it too late to start a computer science degree if I am 20 and don't know any programming languages?",
  "response": "No, it's definitely not too late to start a computer science degree at 20! Many students enter computer science programs without prior programming experience. Here are a few points to consider:\n\n1. **Learning Curve**: Most computer science programs are designed to teach you from the ground up. You'll likely start with introductory courses that cover the basics of programming and computer science principles.\n\n2. **Resources**: There are plenty of online resources, tutorials, and communities where you can start learning programming languages such as Python, Java, or JavaScript on your own. Getting a head start can help you feel more comfortable when classes begin.\n\n3. **Diverse Backgrounds**: Students come from various educational and professional backgrounds. Many successful programmers and computer scientists didn't start learning to code until college or later in life.\n\n4. **Career Opportunities**: The tech industry values skills and problem-solving abilities over traditional pathways. If you\u2019re passionate about computer science, pursuing a degree can open up many rewarding career opportunities.\n\n5. **Networking**: By joining clubs, participating in hackathons, and connecting with peers and professors, you can build a supportive network that will help you as you learn.\n\nStarting your degree might even give you a fresh perspective compared to peers who have been programming for years. Embrace the journey, and don\u2019t hesitate to seek help and resources along the way!",
